00:51:21,880 --> 00:51:22,880
 and there it is.

771
00:51:22,880 --> 00:51:23,880
 It's all kind of ugly and stuff.

772
00:51:23,880 --> 00:51:25,880
 He gets some local anesthetic.

773
00:51:25,880 --> 00:51:28,880
 And local anesthetic, it just numbs the surface.

774
00:51:28,880 --> 00:51:33,880
 And so he kind of injects this local anesthetic onto the lump.

775
00:51:33,880 --> 00:51:36,880
 He opens me up, and then I hear this.

776
00:51:36,880 --> 00:51:40,880
 I hear--now remember, I'm lying face down, facing up the floor,

777
00:51:40,880 --> 00:51:44,880
 and I hear him go, "Oh, my gosh."

778
00:51:44,880 --> 00:51:49,880
 Now, if you're ever in surgery, ladies and gentlemen,

779
00:51:49,880 --> 00:51:54,880
 and you're awake, and you hear the surgeon go, "Oh, my God,

780
00:51:54,880 --> 00:52:00,880
 that is not a good sign," okay, he goes, "Oh, my God," like this.

781
00:52:00,880 --> 00:52:01,880
 He's kind of freaking out.

782
00:52:01,880 --> 00:52:02,880
 I'm lying there.

783
00:52:02,880 --> 00:52:05,880
 I'm like, "Doctor, is there a problem?"

784
00:52:05,880 --> 00:52:10,880
 He's like, "Well," he said, "I've noticed that the cyst is actually

785
00:52:10,880 --> 00:52:13,880
 attached to all of your back muscle.

786
00:52:13,880 --> 00:52:17,880
 It's actually now kind of gotten attached to all of your back muscle."

787
00:52:17,880 --> 00:52:20,880
 Now, what he should have done, if you're making notes,

788
00:52:20,880 --> 00:52:24,880
 what he should have done at this point is sewed me back up, right,

789
00:52:24,880 --> 00:52:28,880
 and then scheduled a proper surgery where I could have general anesthetic,

790
00:52:28,880 --> 00:52:31,880
 get completely knocked out, and he could do whatever he wanted with my back, right?

791
00:52:31,880 --> 00:52:34,880
 Serious surgery.

792
00:52:34,880 --> 00:52:35,880
 He doesn't do that.

793
00:52:35,880 --> 00:52:39,880
 He just decides to keep going.

794
00:52:39,880 --> 00:52:43,880
 So I'm lying there, and I'm in a lot of pain,

795
00:52:43,880 --> 00:52:46,880
 and he's injecting local anesthetic around the wound,

796
00:52:46,880 --> 00:52:49,880
 which is not doing anything because what he's doing now

797
00:52:49,880 --> 00:52:54,880
 is he's pulling out my back muscle, and he's cutting my back muscle

798
00:52:54,880 --> 00:52:58,880
 so that he can free this thing and get it out of me.

799
00:52:58,880 --> 00:53:03,880
 I cannot describe to you how excruciatingly painful it is

800
00:53:03,880 --> 00:53:06,880
 to be completely awake and have somebody,

801
00:53:06,880 --> 00:53:10,880
 "Ee, ee, ee, ee, ee, ping," cutting your back muscle.

802
00:53:10,880 --> 00:53:15,880
 It was no amount of local anesthetic could touch anything

803
00:53:15,880 --> 00:53:17,880
 to the depth of what he was doing.

804
00:53:17,880 --> 00:53:22,880
 In fact, after an hour and a half of him doing this--

805
00:53:22,880 --> 00:53:25,880
 I'm screaming my head off, by the way.

806
00:53:25,880 --> 00:53:28,880
 If anybody was in the waiting room, they left the doctor, right?

807
00:53:28,880 --> 00:53:30,880
 Imagine if you're in the waiting room, right,

808
00:53:30,880 --> 00:53:32,880
 and there's a closed door, and somebody's going, "Aaah!"

809
00:53:32,880 --> 00:53:34,880
 I'm screaming, right?

810
00:53:34,880 --> 00:53:37,880
 They have injected so much local anesthetic into my back

811
00:53:37,880 --> 00:53:40,880
 that they have run out of local anesthetic.

812
00:53:40,880 --> 00:53:42,880
 They no longer--he says to the nurse at one point,

813
00:53:42,880 --> 00:53:44,880
 "More local anesthetic!"

814
00:53:44,880 --> 00:53:47,880
 The nurse says, "We've run out of local anesthetic."

815
00:53:47,880 --> 00:53:51,880
 I am crying and crying and crying, so much pain.

816
00:53:51,880 --> 00:53:53,880
 He then goes to me--he kind of whispers in my ear--

817
00:53:53,880 --> 00:53:56,880
 he said, "Would you like some Valium?"

818
00:53:56,880 --> 00:53:59,880
 Now, apparently, you're not supposed to give Valium

819
00:53:59,880 --> 00:54:01,880
 unless somebody has actually signed off on it, right?

820
00:54:01,880 --> 00:54:04,880
 But I'm in so much pain, and he can see that I'm in so much pain.

821
00:54:04,880 --> 00:54:06,880
 He's like, "Can I give you some Valium?"

822
00:54:06,880 --> 00:54:09,880
 And I'm like, "Please give me Valium, yes!"

823
00:54:09,880 --> 00:54:11,880
 So he injects some Valium into my arm.

824
00:54:11,880 --> 00:54:14,880
 Suddenly, I'm like, "Aaah!"

825
00:54:14,880 --> 00:54:18,880
 The swinging stopped, and I entered into Shalom.

826
00:54:18,880 --> 00:54:20,880
 And it was like I was in heaven,

827
00:54:20,880 --> 00:54:24,880
 and the doctor could do anything he wanted with my back at all.

828
00:54:24,880 --> 00:54:27,880
 I'm like, "Cut away, baby. It doesn't matter. It doesn't matter."

829
00:54:27,880 --> 00:54:29,880
 I couldn't feel anything at that point.

830
00:54:29,880 --> 00:54:31,880
 I was off in some la-la land.

831
00:54:31,880 --> 00:54:35,880
 It took him another about 45 minutes to get the cyst out of my back.

832
00:54:35,880 --> 00:54:37,880
 He sewed me up.

833
00:54:37,880 --> 00:54:40,880
 I had 3 months of physiotherapy on my back--

834
00:54:40,880 --> 00:54:43,880
 how to move my back and move my arm properly again.

835
00:54:43,880 --> 00:54:46,880
 I mean, this was an absolute disaster.

836
00:54:46,880 --> 00:54:48,880
 During the physiotherapy over 3 months,

837
00:54:48,880 --> 00:54:52,880
 God began to speak to me personally out of this trauma.

838
00:54:52,880 --> 00:54:56,880
 He said, "Andrew, you need to understand

839
00:54:56,880 --> 00:54:59,880
 that the way that you treat your sin

840
00:54:59,880 --> 00:55:03,880
 is exactly how you treated your cyst.

841
00:55:03,880 --> 00:55:07,880
 You know that there's some stuff going on in your life.

842
00:55:07,880 --> 00:55:10,880
 You know that there are a few things that are not fully aligned,

843
00:55:10,880 --> 00:55:12,880
 but just kind of like that mirror, you're like,

844
00:55:12,880 --> 00:55:15,880
 'Oh, yeah. Well, it's not hurting me.

845
00:55:15,880 --> 00:55:17,880
 It's not really hurting anyone else.

846
00:55:17,880 --> 00:55:21,880
 It's really not such a big deal. I'll just carry on.'"

847
00:55:21,880 --> 00:55:26,880
 And God was like, "Andrew, you just walk on and carry on with your sin

848
00:55:26,880 --> 00:55:28,880
 until it actually starts hurting yourself,

849
00:55:28,880 --> 00:55:30,880
 until it actually does something.

850
00:55:30,880 --> 00:55:33,880
 Maybe you get caught in something, or maybe somebody finds out,

851
00:55:33,880 --> 00:55:37,880
 or maybe you realize that it's impacting a relationship in your life

852
00:55:37,880 --> 00:55:38,880
 or something like that.

853
00:55:38,880 --> 00:55:40,880
 Then you're willing to deal with it.

854
00:55:40,880 --> 00:55:42,880
 But even then, you're just like the doctor.

855
00:55:42,880 --> 00:55:44,880
 "Oh, just open it up, pop it out, zip it back up.

856
00:55:44,880 --> 00:55:46,880
 It's no big deal. It's fine. I can handle it.

857
00:55:46,880 --> 00:55:50,880
 It's just a minor thing. It's not a major sin. It's a minor sin."

858
00:55:50,880 --> 00:55:53,880
 By the way, the Bible doesn't talk about sins in that way.

859
00:55:53,880 --> 00:55:56,880
 But we so often do, "It's just a minor thing. It's not a big deal.

860
00:55:56,880 --> 00:55:59,880
 We just don't understand fully the impact."

861
00:55:59,880 --> 00:56:01,880
 And I felt like God was saying, "Andrew, you don't fully get it.

862
00:56:01,880 --> 00:56:05,880
 You don't fully see that actually your sin goes so much deeper

863
00:56:05,880 --> 00:56:07,880
 than what you just see on the surface.

864
00:56:07,880 --> 00:56:12,880
 You see maybe anger, but you don't realize what the depth of that is

865
00:56:12,880 --> 00:56:14,880
 and why it is that you're so angry.

866
00:56:14,880 --> 00:56:18,880
 You see lust and some of the issues that you struggle with in that area,

867
00:56:18,880 --> 00:56:20,880
 but you don't understand the roots of that.

868
00:56:20,880 --> 00:56:23,880
 You think it's just an easy thing, something to quickly deal with,

869
00:56:23,880 --> 00:56:27,880
 when actually your sin so deeply is entangled with you

870
00:56:27,880 --> 00:56:32,880
 that no local anesthetic of you just trying to be a good Christian,

871
00:56:32,880 --> 00:56:34,880
 of you just trying to be a better person,

872
00:56:34,880 --> 00:56:38,880
 of you just trying to go to church more is going to solve the reality

873
00:56:38,880 --> 00:56:41,880
 that there are some sins in your life that you're carrying around with you

874
00:56:41,880 --> 00:56:44,880
 and you're not willing to truly deal with.

875
00:56:44,880 --> 00:56:46,880
 You're just trying to put a band-aid on something

876
00:56:46,880 --> 00:56:49,880
 that's going to require some valium and some uprooting

877
00:56:49,880 --> 00:56:52,880
 at the very root of what it's entangled into.

878
00:56:52,880 --> 00:56:54,880
 Are you with me?

879
00:56:54,880 --> 00:56:58,880
 I'm a pastor of a church, and I think I'm a pretty good person,

880
00:56:58,880 --> 00:57:00,880
 and I do my best to walk with Jesus,

881
00:57:00,880 --> 00:57:07,880
 and I realized that sin in my life had gone far deeper

882
00:57:07,880 --> 00:57:09,880
 than perhaps it should have.

883
00:57:09,880 --> 00:57:12,880
 And what I thought was something I could pop out and deal with in my lunch break

884
00:57:12,880 --> 00:57:15,880
 was actually something that I needed to go on a journey with the Lord

885
00:57:15,880 --> 00:57:20,880
 and to see the freedom that He truly wanted for me.

886
00:57:20,880 --> 00:57:23,880
 It's interesting because Scripture speaks about sin this way.

887
00:57:23,880 --> 00:57:26,880
 Let me read you this beautiful verse from Hebrews 12, verse 1.

888
00:57:26,880 --> 00:57:31,880
 It says this, "Therefore, since we are surrounded by such a great cloud of witnesses,

889
00:57:31,880 --> 00:57:36,880
 let us throw off everything that hinders and the sin that so easily entangles."

890
00:57:36,880 --> 00:57:38,880
 Notice that.

891
00:57:38,880 --> 00:57:42,880
 "The sin that is not surface, the sin that we think is surface,

892
00:57:42,880 --> 00:57:47,880
 and it's no big deal, but it so easily entangles in so much of us.

893
00:57:47,880 --> 00:57:51,880
 And let us run with perseverance the race marked out for us."

894
00:57:51,880 --> 00:57:53,880
 I love the writer to Hebrews here.

895
00:57:53,880 --> 00:57:56,880
 He's speaking to the church, and he's saying, "Church, you've got to understand

896
00:57:56,880 --> 00:57:58,880
 that there is a great cloud of witnesses.

897
00:57:58,880 --> 00:58:01,880
 There are men and women who through all the history have gone on a journey

898
00:58:01,880 --> 00:58:04,880
 and walking with God, and we need to throw off everything

899
00:58:04,880 --> 00:58:07,880
 because there is a race that God is calling us to run.

900
00:58:07,880 --> 00:58:09,880
 There is something that God is calling you to do.

901
00:58:09,880 --> 00:58:13,880
 There's a part of who you are that you are created and shaped and formed by God.

902
00:58:13,880 --> 00:58:15,880
 God is doing something in your life.

903
00:58:15,880 --> 00:58:17,880
 He's using in your workplace, in your family.

904
00:58:17,880 --> 00:58:19,880
 There's a purpose. There's a mission.

905
00:58:19,880 --> 00:58:22,880
 There's a race to run, and he's saying there is this race,

906
00:58:22,880 --> 00:58:25,880
 but in order to run that race, in order to do that,

907
00:58:25,880 --> 00:58:28,880
 you've got to throw off the things that are holding you back,

908
00:58:28,880 --> 00:58:30,880
 the things that are weighing you down.

909
00:58:30,880 --> 00:58:34,880
 And he says, "The sin that so easily entangles."

910
00:58:34,880 --> 00:58:41,880
 The word for "entangles" here in the Greek means literally trapped, ensnared.

911
00:58:41,880 --> 00:58:43,880
 It means hidden.

912
00:58:43,880 --> 00:58:47,880
 "The sin that so easily is not just the surface stuff,

913
00:58:47,880 --> 00:58:51,880
 but the stuff that is so much deeper than that."

914
00:58:51,880 --> 00:58:55,880
 It's like the writer in Hebrews is saying, "I want to invite you on a journey,

915
00:58:55,880 --> 00:58:59,880
 a journey where you can truly be free."

916
00:58:59,880 --> 00:59:03,880
 When the doctor finally got my cyst out and managed to cut all the stuff

917
00:59:03,880 --> 00:59:06,880
 that needed to be cut out, it never returned

918
00:59:06,880 --> 00:59:10,880
 because he had dealt not just with the surface issue but with the roots.

919
00:59:10,880 --> 00:59:15,880
 And the thing that the Holy Spirit has for us as believers in Jesus

920
00:59:15,880 --> 00:59:20,880
 is the joy of knowing a God who truly can get to the roots,

921
00:59:20,880 --> 00:59:23,880
 not just deal with some of the stuff that we find

922
00:59:23,880 --> 00:59:28,880
 on the surface of our relationship with Him.

923
00:59:28,880 --> 00:59:30,880
 God actually gives us a tool.

924
00:59:30,880 --> 00:59:34,880
 He gives us a gift in order to be able to really get to the roots

925
00:59:34,880 --> 00:59:39,880
 of our sin and our brokenness, and it's the gift of confession and repentance.

926
00:59:39,880 --> 00:59:42,880
 And again, I know that confession and repentance seems like a really heavy topic.

927
00:59:42,880 --> 00:59:46,880
 It seems like something that we kind of don't want to go to church to hear about that.

928
00:59:46,880 --> 00:59:48,880
 That seems like something that's a little overwhelming.

929
00:59:48,880 --> 00:59:51,880
 But when you think of confession and repentance,

930
00:59:51,880 --> 00:59:55,880
 what I want you to actually be thinking about is freedom and intimacy

931
00:59:55,880 --> 00:59:58,880
 because confession and repentance is really just a process

932
00:59:58,880 --> 01:00:00,880
 of bringing freedom and intimacy into your life.

933
01:00:00,880 --> 01:00:04,880
 And so when the Bible speaks about confession and repentance,

934
01:00:04,880 --> 01:00:08,880
 our natural response is to often think of the negative side of that,

935
01:00:08,880 --> 01:00:11,880
 but the Bible so often presents it more as the journey

936
01:00:11,880 --> 01:00:13,880
 and what it brings you into.

937
01:00:13,880 --> 01:00:16,880
 It brings you actually into a profound place of greater freedom in your life

938
01:00:16,880 --> 01:00:17,880
 and intimacy with God.

939
01:00:17,880 --> 01:00:21,880
 And if this whole series over January has been about fresh encounters,

940
01:00:21,880 --> 01:00:25,880
 if your fast has been about a desire to be in deeper intimacy with Christ,

941
01:00:25,880 --> 01:00:29,880
 then confession and repentance is perhaps the greatest tool

942
01:00:29,880 --> 01:00:34,880
 that God has given you to bring you into a place of fresher encounter with Him.

943
01:00:34,880 --> 01:00:40,880
 In fact, the writer in the book of Acts, which we know of as Luke,

944
01:00:40,880 --> 01:00:45,880
 he writes it this way in Acts 3, starting in verse 19.

945
01:00:45,880 --> 01:00:50,880
 He says, "Repent then and turn to God so that your sins will be wiped out

946
01:00:50,880 --> 01:00:54,880
 and that times of refreshing may come from the presence of the Lord."

947
01:00:54,880 --> 01:00:56,880
 Isn't that beautiful?

948
01:00:56,880 --> 01:01:00,880
 Notice how Scripture speaks about the work of confession and repentance.

949
01:01:00,880 --> 01:01:02,880
 It doesn't wrap it up in some fear.

950
01:01:02,880 --> 01:01:03,880
 It wraps it up in joy.

951
01:01:03,880 --> 01:01:07,880
 It says, "When we confess, when we repent,

952
01:01:07,880 --> 01:01:10,880
 we turn from the brokenness and the bad stuff,

953
01:01:10,880 --> 01:01:13,880
 and we find ourselves in times of refreshing with the Lord."

954
01:01:13,880 --> 01:01:18,880
 In the Greek, when you read that, the emphasis is in the times of refreshing.

955
01:01:18,880 --> 01:01:22,880
 It's like Luke is saying, "Hey, guys, this is the joy of knowing Jesus.

956
01:01:22,880 --> 01:01:23,880
 This is actually what it's about.

957
01:01:23,880 --> 01:01:25,880
 You want to know what intimacy is with Him?

958
01:01:25,880 --> 01:01:30,880
 It is confessing and repenting the stuff that so easily entangles in us.

959
01:01:30,880 --> 01:01:34,880
 It is taking seriously the fact that we walk so often in brokenness,

960
01:01:34,880 --> 01:01:37,880
 and in releasing ourselves from that, we have times of refreshing

961
01:01:37,880 --> 01:01:39,880
 in the presence of the Lord."

962
01:01:39,880 --> 01:01:43,880
 It's like this great invitation into something that is far more profound

963
01:01:43,880 --> 01:01:45,880
 than we ever realized.

964
01:01:45,880 --> 01:01:48,880
 And the problem is that so often through the history of church,

965
01:01:48,880 --> 01:01:53,880
 the church has talked about confession and repentance as a scary thing,

966
01:01:53,880 --> 01:01:57,880
 as if there's some God who's super angry at us,

967
01:01:57,880 --> 01:02:02,880
 a God who is so angry at us that He's punishing us in wrath

968
01:02:02,880 --> 01:02:05,880
 for the broken things that we struggle with.

969
01:02:05,880 --> 01:02:09,880
 And I think one of the things that we need to do to free ourselves as Christians

970
01:02:09,880 --> 01:02:12,880
 is we actually need to make a shift in our mindset away from thinking

971
01:02:12,880 --> 01:02:16,880
 about confession and repentance from a fear-based perspective,

972
01:02:16,880 --> 01:02:19,880
 but actually think about it from a joy-based perspective.

973
01:02:19,880 --> 01:02:22,880
 I mean, could you imagine what it would be like if we all thought

974
01:02:22,880 --> 01:02:25,880
 that confession and repentance is a joy?

975
01:02:25,880 --> 01:02:26,880
 Like, what a gift.

976
01:02:26,880 --> 01:02:30,880
 What a joy it is to not have to walk around with my brokenness all the time,

977
01:02:30,880 --> 01:02:33,880
 but to realize that Jesus went to the cross, shed His blood,

978
01:02:33,880 --> 01:02:38,880
 so that I would be free, so that I would know times of refreshing from the Lord.

979
01:02:38,880 --> 01:02:41,880
 So that would be the constant state that I find myself in,

980
01:02:41,880 --> 01:02:46,880
 not the state of feeling guilty or shame or a state of feeling like I've got a God

981
01:02:46,880 --> 01:02:50,880
 who's angry at me, but instead the reality is I have a God who loves me

982
01:02:50,880 --> 01:02:57,880
 and, yes, sees sin, sees what sin does to me, hates sin, but loves me.

983
01:02:57,880 --> 01:03:01,880
 And because God hates sin but loves me, when He sees that I'm in sin,

984
01:03:01,880 --> 01:03:04,880
 what He sees is not I'm angry at this person.

985
01:03:04,880 --> 01:03:08,880
 What God says is there's a race that I want this person to run,

986
01:03:08,880 --> 01:03:11,880
 and if they're struggling under the yoke and the brokenness

987
01:03:11,880 --> 01:03:16,880
 and the entanglement of this sin, they can't run as free as I want them to run.

988
01:03:16,880 --> 01:03:20,880
 I wonder if you could sense this, that the Holy Spirit looks over you today

989
01:03:20,880 --> 01:03:23,880
 and He says, "Man, I see so much for you.

990
01:03:23,880 --> 01:03:26,880
 I see so much in your life.

991
01:03:26,880 --> 01:03:29,880
 I see so much that I want to take you in and draw you into.

992
01:03:29,880 --> 01:03:32,880
 This is the great joy of God for you.

993
01:03:32,880 --> 01:03:37,880
 He loves you so much. He wants to release you into that."

994
01:03:37,880 --> 01:03:40,880
 Imagine what it would be like if we came here on Sundays

995
01:03:40,880 --> 01:03:46,880
 in the joy of being honest about our sin and our brokenness,

996
01:03:46,880 --> 01:03:51,880
 knowing not that we celebrate it, not at all,

997
01:03:51,880 --> 01:03:57,880
 but knowing that as we confess it, as we speak of it, as we recognize it,

998
01:03:57,880 --> 01:04:02,880
 as we take ownership for it, we are releasing ourselves

999
01:04:02,880 --> 01:04:05,880
 into the race that Christ has called us to run

1000
01:04:05,880 --> 01:04:10,880
 and at times of refreshing of the invitation.

1001
01:04:10,880 --> 01:04:12,880
 I love how Tim Keller puts this.

